attributes.title: Virus Naming Study
attributes.description:
This study investigates the impact of naming on psychological reactions to the current 2020 pandemic. The specific focus is on three outcomes 1) Anxiety and Risk Perception, 2) Perceptions of the virus contagiousness and social impact, and 3) Sinophobia (i.e. anti-chinese prejudice)
A rich literature on the psychology of naming has shown how a subtle label can significantly effect perceptions of natural disasters and inanimate objects. This paper investigates whether such mechanisms are at play in the current pandemic and if so how this might be addressed.

q1.value: Theo Masters-Waage, Neal Jha, Jochen Reb

q2.value:
Hypothesis 1: Naming of the virus will differentially impact a) anxiety/risk perception, b) beliefs about the mortality/contagiousness, and c) Sinophobia.

Hypothesis 2a: Compared to Wuhan Virus, the two scientific names (COVID-19 and coronavirus) will lead to greater levels of anxiety, higher perceived domain specific risk and stronger beliefs about the mortality and contagiousness of the virus.

Hypothesis 2b: Compared to the COVID-19 and coronavirus, the eponymous name associated with China (Wuhan Virus) will lead to greater levels of Sinophobia.

Note, no specific hypotheses are made as to how the effect of naming will vary across the countries tested but this will be examined in exploratory analyses.

q3.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: Personnel who analyze the data collected from the study are not aware of the treatment applied to any given group.

q5.value: When coding the data one researcher will randomly assign a number to each condition. The research who conducts the analysis will then be blind to which number represents which group. After analysis the numbers will be reassigned to the groups.

question.value:
Between subjects with 3 conditions (COVID-19, Coronavirus, and Wuhan Virus).

These three conditions will be tested across 4 countries (US, Canada, India and Singapore)

q7.value:
Individuals will be randomly assigned to one of the three naming conditions. 

The same procedure will be conducted across all 4 countries.

q8.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value:
All participants will be collected using an the online platform MTurk and paid $0.70 for the completion of the 5 minute survey.

Sample: Four samples will be collected across 4 countries; USA, Canada, Singapore and India. All samples will be uploaded on the same day.

Inclusion Criteria: Only participants with an approval rating of 95% or above and having completed at least 50 surveys (hits) on MTurk will be recruited for the study. Additionally, participants must be at least 18 years old.

Exclusions: 
1. Given the subtle nature of this experiment's manipulation, individuals will be excluded for failing an instructional manipulation check question included in the study (Oppenheimer, Meyvis, & Davidenko, 2009). Version of the IMC is attached.

2. Individuals will be excluded if they a) currently have the virus or b) had close contact with someone with the virus. This exclusion criteria is included because such factors may strongly impact anxiety and perceptions of the virus.

q12.value:
Previous research investigating the effect of naming in the health psychology literature used a sample size of 189. 
Petrie, K. J., MacKrill, K., Derksen, C., & Dalbeth, N. (2018). An illness by any other name: The effect of renaming gout on illness and treatment perceptions. Health Psychology, 37(1), 37.

Given that exclusions are likely due to the different criteria employed a buffer of 30 is obtained.

q13.value: If below 180 individuals are obtained for one of the sample then additional data will be collected this decision will be made before conducting the analyses.

question.value:
We will manipulated the name given to the virus in an article (example uploaded) and in all following questions referring to the virus (e.g. what do you think the economic impact of [COVID-19 or Coronavirus or Wuhan Virus] will be?). 
The three names used are: 1) COVID-19, 2) Coronavirus and 3) Wuhan Virus.

Note: Manipulations are shown in attached file named "Manipulations".
Note: Participants will only be able to advance from the article (i.e. manipulation) after viewing it for at least 10 seconds.

Four outcome variables will be included in the study: 

1) State Anxiety: Measured using the the state PANAS-X fear sub-scale.

2) Domain Specific Risk Perception: An adaptation of the DOSPERT scale (Blais & Weber, 2006) with scenarios that relate specifically to the current pandemic.

3) Perceptions of Mortality and Contagiousness of the disease: Measures adopted from a recent paper on the effects of the virus (Fetzer, Hensel, Hermle, & Roth, 2020).

4) Sinophobia: Using a scale developed by Payne et al. (2010) which explicitly asks for individuals perceptions of individuals warmth/coldness along with sympathy and admiration towards them. This was adapted to refer to Chinese individuals. Note, this measure was used based on its predictive capacity of prejudice behavior (see Axt, 2017)

NOTE: All outcome variables are included in the attached file name "Measures".

Demographic variables include age, sex, country residence (should be predetermined, see "inclusion criteria"), household income and nationality. We will also include a measure of political orientation for exploratory analyses.

1) State Anxiety: As done by the original authors, items will be averaged across all six items to form a measure of state anxiety.

2) Domain Specific Risk Perception: As done by the original authors, items will be averaged across all six items to form a measure of domain specific. However, given that this scale was heavily edited if the alpha value is low principle component analyses will be run to see if certain items warrant exclusion. For example, there could be floor/ceiling effects on some of the items that negatively impact reliability.

3) Perceptions of Mortality and Contagiousness of the disease: These are single item measures

4) Sinophobia: Three single item measures. Note the warmth measure must be converted into a single item measure using a simple transformation. Answers to original question of "neither warm nor cold" are coded as 4, then answers to the follow up on coldness are coded as 1 "extremely cold" to 3 " little cold" and follow up on warmness are coded as 5 "little warm" and 7 "extremely warm".

All analyses will be conducted in STATA.

To evaluate Hypothesis 1 four separate ANOVAs will be run assessing how naming impacts each of the four outcome variable (anxiety, risk attitude, perceptions of virus spread, and Sinophobia). Significant effects of naming across any of these will be interpreted as support for hypothesis 1.

Post hoc analyses will then compare the direction of such effects to see if they support hypotheses 2a-2c. For example, if naming significant effects Sinophobia, then post-hoc tukey tests will evaluate whether the Wuhan Virus specifically leads to greater levels of Sinophobia compared to the other conditions.

These analyses will be conducted across each national sample separately and then data will be pooled from across the four samples to test the models using the full data set.

These analyses will be presented in the format of the attached figure (file named "Figure X")

q19.value:
Significance in terms of frequentists analysis will be based on two-tailed tests with .05 as the significance threshold; values between  .05 and .1 will be referred to as marginal.

Bayes factors will be interpreted as follows: 1-3 Anecdotal, 3-10 Moderate, 10-30 Strong, 30-100 Very strong, 100+ Extreme.
(Note, if no evidence is found for the alternate hypothesis tests will be run for the null)

q20.value:
Exclusions: 
1. Given the subtle nature of this experiment's manipulation, individuals will be excluded for failing an instructional manipulation check question included in the study (Oppenheimer, Meyvis, & Davidenko, 2009). Version of the IMC is attached.

2. Individuals will be excluded if they a) currently have the virus, b) had contact with someone with the virus and/or c) has a close friend or family member with the virus. This exclusion criteria is included because such factors may strongly impact anxiety and perceptions of the virus.

q21.value: Participants will be included for every full outcome measure that they complete.

q22.value:
Additional exploratory analyses could look at any striking differences that arise across cultures or differences depending on the level of contamination in the country (High = US & India; Low = Canada & Singapore)

Exploratory analyses will also investigate the effect of political orientation on the effect of naming. The scale used will be:

Exploratory analyses will investigate mediating relationship of affect on the other outcomes; e.g. is the process by which naming that impacts risk attitude mediated by anxiety?

attributes.title: The Effects of Women-Only Mentoring Workshops in Academic Political Science

q1.value: The Effects of Women-Only Mentoring Workshops in Academic Political Science

q2.value: Tali Mendelberg | Andrew Tyner | Lisa Argyle

q8.value: Registration prior to realization of outcomes

q15.value: The gender gap in the ranks of academia is a well-known problem, one which extends to the field of political science. Although men and women earn PhDs in political science in roughly equal numbers, only 7% of full professors at research universities are women (Monroe and Chiu 2010). Dozens of solutions have been proposed to mitigate these challenges (see APSA 2016), but our extensive literature review finds that very few solutions have been rigorously evaluated. There is one intervention with demonstrated positive causal impact on women’s research productivity, in the field of economics: mentoring workshops for women. The American Economics Association’s Committee on the Status of Women in the Economics Profession (CSWEP) hosts an annual two-day mentoring workshop for women, called CeMENT. For several years, admissions to CeMENT were fully randomized among qualified applicants. Blau et al. (2010) evaluated the CVs of women who applied and were admitted compared to women who applied but were not admitted, for up to five years after the conference. They find that CeMENT attendance substantially increased these applicants’ number of federal grants, top-tier publications, and total publications. We are undertaking a replication and extension of CeMENT for women in political science.

q16.value: Does the APSA Women's Research Mentoring Workshop advance participants' careers? Do the following mechanisms help explain the relationship between mentoring workshops and career advancement: developing a peer network; receiving high-quality mentorship from senior colleagues; identifying role models; receiving useful feedback on work-in-progress; confidence- building; developing resilience; developing a sense of belonging in the profession; acquiring professionalization information; or being in an all-women environment?

q17.value: We are undertaking a replication and extension of CeMENT for women in political science. The study includes randomized admission to the workshop from the pool of applicants, a baseline wave administered to all applicants, several waves of post- treatment surveys of all applicants, and comparisons of annually collected CVs. The conference will be held in Washington, DC on October 12-13, 2018, and NSF grant money and funds from the American Political Science Association are financing travel, meals, and lodging for all attendees and mentors. As part of the application process, junior scholars submitted a one-page statement of research interests and the abstract of a working paper they would present if selected. We used these materials to group applicants by research interest, and four applicants were randomly selected to attend within each working group. Each working group was assigned one senior (tenured) female faculty mentor, as a replication of CeMENT. The workshop schedule is modeled after CeMENT. Each attendee circulated a paper draft or similar research document (i.e. a grant proposal) to their working group prior to the conference. Each attendee has been allocated a one-hour session with their working group to receive specific suggestions for improvement of their research. Additionally, six plenary sessions will be held for all participants, featuring panel discussions by mentors and Q&A time on career-relevant topics. Meals are designated for unstructured networking and mentoring conversations. Details on how the effects of the workshop will be tested are contained in the pre- analysis plan.

attributes.title: PSA [006] - Moral thinking across the world
attributes.description: Research on moral reasoning is centered around moral dilemmas in which deontological perspectives (emphasizing individual rights) are in conflict with consequentialist reasoning (also referred to as utilitarian; following the greater good). A central finding of this field is that people in certain situations are more likely do go with deontological considerations, while in other cases they are more likely to decide based on consequentialist reasons. In their seminal article, Greene et al. (2009) tried to investigate the effect of situational and psychological factors (e.g., intent of the agent, or physical contact between the agent and victim) on people’s moral decisions, but their work could not explore the effect of a potentially important component: culture. Therefore, the goal of the present research proposal is to empirically test the universality of utilitarian and deontological responding by directly replicating Greene et al.’s experiments on non-WEIRD samples as well as to explore the influence of culture and economic status on moral reasoning.

q2.value: I hypothesize that people who workout with a partner will have a higher intensity workout and average heart rate. A predicted effect of working out with a partner is the motivation to do better when in front of someone.

q3.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: This is a within study design, which requires 40 participants. 2 (age) x 2 (environment)

q8.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: I gathered 20 women from different athletic teams at Saint Joseph's University, who agreed to include one of their parents. The total 40 participants were given a direction sheet in which told them they would need to do the same workout together, then repeat the workout once more alone, while collecting their average heart rates for both completed workouts. Once they have completed both, they are directed to my survey in which collects their average heart rate data, and other questions that have reduced the amount if confounds for the study, (demographics, if they are in school, level of fitness, duration of workout).  And a within subject design, considering that both ages, under and below 50 are completing the same tasks.

q11.value: Ideally, I will have a within subjects design. I will have 20 per age group, giving me a total of 40 participants, since the environment is controlled for both. The only difference is the age. I already have recruited the number I need to complete this research.

q12.value: My professor said I would need 40 participants to complete this study. This is why I added age as a component, it was too hard to find 40 athletes, when I could just find 20 and get them to workout with their partners. I asked over 45 athletes for their consent, as well as their parents and only 20 gave consent. I stopped asking more athletes until I got to that point.

q13.value: I don't need to plan to stop my data because I have the exact amount of participants needed.

question.value:
I manipulated the age of my participants, as well as the environment they are working out in. The environment is defined as both: working out with a partner and alone. The age is defined as under 50, and over 50. 
What is your age?
Question Type

What is your preference? 
*
Alone
With a partner
No preference

The measured variable is the level of intensity of workout in both environments. Participants are using heart rate technology to collect data for both environments, which will be inputted into the survey they will fill once they are done.
Simple math will be used to compare the average heart rates for both of the workouts. The higher their heart rate average, the higher the intensity.
ANAVO for the main effect of higher intensity while working out with a partner.
